title: Nyantomo Purr Fect Potty Starter Kit for Kittens
reviewText: This potty starter kit is a cleverly-designed litter box aimed for young cats.  What I am finding is that my older, fat cat likes this too, as he doesn't have to lift his legs so high to get into this box.  This tells me this device would be ideal for older, more arthritic cats who are not too picky about their bathrooms.My fat cat doesn't mind the pellets, but I also know from using pellets at an animal shelter, that not all cats like the pellet texture for their bathroom essentials.  It's a learned habit.The device does work as advertised.  The pellets cover up the poop, and the pee falls below the top half to fall into the absorbent pad below.  Odors are concealed for a good week, but that depends on how often it's used.  My big, fat cat will fill this up in a few days.  The pellets do get saturated and become mushy, and cats don't like to do their business on mushy flats. Refills may appear expensive if they are replaced with the brand pellets, but the contraption is usable regardless of what is used for the material.  I can buy pine pellets at the local feed store.The bin is made of hard plastic and is well-made.  There is no seam anywhere on either one; they appear to be made from a mold.  I'm tempted to give this a five-star rating if this little litter box does its job under a variety of materials.

title: Iams Grain Free Naturals Chicken and Garden Pea Dog Dry Food, 9.3-Pound
reviewText: Dog food is so tricky - on the one hand you have to trust the label for all the information they give, and you select hoping you are giving your beloved puppy the healthiest and best options. And on the other hand, someone else has to eat it.  Our dog is a super picky eater and has rejected a lot of expensive and highly recommended dog food for no good reason that I can see.  He loves this one, and eats it happily, so that's a double yes for us -  all the information on the label sounds so good and the dog will eat it! title: Instinct Grain-Free Beef Formula Canned Dog Food by Nature's Variety, 5.5-Ounce Cans (Pack of 12)
reviewText: We bought this on the basis of Amazon reviews for our new puppy.  It's really strong smelling from the can,  which humans don't like,  but dogs may.  The food looks wetter, there is a gravy to it,  which I imagine is a good thing.  Our dog is a picky eater and sometimes gulps this down but at other don't won't and leaves it in his bowl for some time.  My biggest complaint is that it is just as stinky coming out as going in.  We live in an apartment and our dog is paper trained,  but that means that he sometimes goes indoors.  His elimination was both wetter  and much smellier after eating this food,  as compared to the other dog food we bought him.  Even when he goes in the park,  it's harder to pick up and often leaves a smear,  which I hate. That alone is reason for me not to buy this again.  If you have a yard dog,  it may not matter as much.

title: Four Paws Wee-Wee Puppy Housebreaking Pads
reviewText: we just got a new puppy and I haven't had a puppy in a long,  long time.  The thing I was most anxious about was accidents all over the house.  We live in an apartment and he will have to use them between walks for the rest of his life  (not just puppyhood)He had a little bit of familiarity with the pads,  but he's taken to them beautifully.  I don't know what smell/attractant they use but it seems to really work for us.  And it hasn't leaked through once.  Admittedly he is a small dog,  but he doesn't even seem to go to the edges,  instead he goes right to the center each time.  We paid $25 for the 100 pack, apparently reduced from close to $60.  We may stock up incase the price goes up!!

title: Petnation Port-A-Crate E2 Indoor/Outdoor Pet Home
reviewText: I wasn't sure of the size and wanted something my dog could turn around in, if he wanted to.  We bought the 24" and it works just fine as a sleep crate.  I didn't realize how big it would be (my fault,  not the items!) and also didn't realize that the larger sizes don't come with handles. This is not a travel crate, it is a sleep crate.  I don't mind that at all,  I bought it primarily for him to sleep in and also to stay in for housetraining,  and I wanted something a bit roomier, but the smaller one with handles would have had a dual usage in that you could take the dog to the vet in it.  You could put this in your own car,  but we don't have a car and it's a bit too big to put in a taxi, and a bit cumbersome to carry.We also lined it with the Midwest Quiet Time Pet Bed 18" and that goes in perfectly and he's very cozy sleeping in it with the lining.  I would recommend some sort of lining,  as the floor is just a flat plastic.  I like the dual openings - the size and the top,  so we can put him in it to sleep and then leave it open during the day for him to wander in and out at will.  It's a great color,  it sits quietly in our living room, and doesn't clash with anything.  I would buy it again.

title: Back to Basics Grain-Free Dry Dog Food
reviewText: It's hard to review something that someone else has to eat.  From a human point of view the food looks good and smells fine,  but the packaging leaves something to be desired:  it's a tear open top and can't be resealed, so you have to find a clip to keep it closed. From our puppy's point of view this was a no go.  He just wouldn't eat it,  have no idea why.  We tried twice,  got no traction,  and so stopped.  Our dog is a particularly fussy eater - not fancy,  but fussy - so I don't really know what to make of that,  other than to recommend that you buy a small sample of any new food first, to see if your dog will like it.

title: Aria Feather Dog Bows Canister, 100-Pack
reviewText: These are adorable. I took them out of the plastic canister because the tape holding the lid on didn't come off cleanly and the feathers kept sticking to it. That process was a bit messy, but now they are cleanly zipped away in a baggie. The rubber band is a bit difficult to apply, but it stays in really well. I have to make a point of taking the feather/bow out once a week so that she doesn't mat and tangle there. If I had a complaint, it would be the colors. I love the purple on my pup, and if given the option, I would order an entire canister of the purple. The green is ok (she is strawberry blonde). Yellow and red are not good with her hair color, but would be amazing on a black doggie. Just like with people, certain colors look good and others don't. These bows are so inexpensive, though, that I will just not use the ones I don't like. Maybe I can find someone with a little black dog?

title: Greenies Pill Pockets Tablets, 3.2-Ounce
reviewText: I have to give my dogs Cosequin for their joints. They get half a tablet every other day. Half a tablet does not fit in the pocket. The pocket splits open and won't hold the pill. I've had better luck using Kraft American Cheese singles to get them to take their pills. I just wrap a small strip of cheese around the tablet and smush it together. The dogs do LOVE the taste of these, though. A quarter of a tablet fits OK in these smaller pockets. I can only imagine a WHOLE baby aspirin fitting in without splitting the pocket in half.UPDATE - I've opened the second (of three) bag and these are MUCH better. The first bag must have been old, as the pockets were dry and couldn't be manipulated. These are soft, like play-doh, and I can easily squish them around my dogs' tablets. Giant plus: I can use ONE pill pocket to administer pills to THREE dogs. I break the pocket into three parts, smash it flat, wrap it around the pill and all three take their joint supplements.

title: Pet ID Tag - Paw Print Jewelry Tag - Custom engraved cat and dog ID tags. Jewelry that ensures pet safety.
reviewText: I got two of these for new puppies. They arrived quickly and were certainly adorable. I attached them to my dogs' collar by threading the collar through the ring, the way I have always done. The tag sat perpendicular to the dogs'  chests. Awkward. I emailed the company and they said you are supposed to hook the keyring to the D ring on the dogs'  collars. Oh, stupid me! So, I did and it was fine (except that when the leash is attached to the D ring, it spins the collar around so that the tags are behind their heads instead of all cute under their chin AND the spinning around pulls their hair). Still workable, I just bought harnesses to use for their walks instead of fastening the leash to the collar. Then the dogs' license and rabies and microchip tags came and the hole on all those tags runs through the tag itself, which means I cannot simply put those on the same ring behind the cute decorative tag. I had to put another ring on for those tags. For some reason, the two rings keep changing places and the ugly rabies tag ends up on top of the cute rage. I gave up.  Ultimately, I ordered the same design from another company that has the hole going the same way as all the other tags (through the tag, front to back). I guess I just can't figure it out. Unless I am really missing something here, you can't put this tag on the same ring as other regular tags. If that doesn't matter to you OR if you have a big enough collar that you HAVE to put the ring on the D ring, then you might absolutely love these.  I just wanted my experience out there because it is something I didn't even think about until I was trying to put them on my dogs. I have tiny (6-9 pound pomeranians)dogs, if that helps at all.

title: 100% Waterproof Mambe Pet Blanket
reviewText: We have two puppies who are ALMOST potty trained and an adult pomeranian. We let them sleep on our bed, but we were putting a waterproof mattress pad (with the round corners cut off) over our comforter, then putting a cotton blanket on top of that. By morning, the blanket and the pad are on the floor, the puppies are on the comforter, and I've been doing more laundry than I care to. This size is perfect for a king-sized bed. At first, I was worried because there wasn't any hang-over on the sides (the long way, it covers a king bed side to side perfectly). The cool thing is that it won't slip or slide on the bed, so the puppies have no choice but to sleep on top of it. I got two of the small ones too, and they fit about the same way on a double bed (my kids like to have them sleep with them too). It doesn't make the bed much warmer than it would otherwise be (our old solution was just too hot). The blankets arrived quickly. The only thing is that it is black on one side and brown on the other - not a huge deal, but I bought the brown because it coordinates with the bedding in both rooms, whereas black totally clashes. I probably would still have bought them, though, because there isn't really anything else like this that I could find that got as good of reviews. I haven't washed it yet (hooray for the puppies), and if I run into any problems with that I will update this review. It is April of 2014. If you're still seeing this and I haven't updated it, everything went fine. UPDATE (June 19th): I have washed the two brown blankets several times exactly as the instructions said to. I have washed the cream blanket once. The two brown blankets have completely become un-laminated, so I have the equivalent of huge pillow cases on the beds now. This does not seem to impact the waterproof-ness of the product, but does make it hard to lint-roll the fuzz off of them. A lint roller is the only way I've found to get the dog hair off of them - it doesn't come off in the wash, but forms little balls that are hard to pick off. Vacuuming with a hand vac for pet hair is not an option - haven't even tried. Pledge Fabric Sweeper for pet hair worked before they became un-laminated, but not anymore. The lint roller is the only option, but now that they are de-laminated, the top layer sticks to the lint roller and rolls around it, so it takes 3 people to clean off the pet hair (2 people to stretch the blanket and hold it taut, and another to roll the surface. I opened the cream blanket last night and my pup (recovering from surgery) wet it. I washed it but hung it to dry indoors in hopes of avoiding the de-lamination. It seems fine after the one washing (gentle cycle cold water, just like I've done with the other two). I expect that it will separate like the other two. This makes me a bit resentful, as the blankets were quite expensive.

title: Doggles Dgorlg16 Originalz Large Chrome Frames / Smoke Lenses
reviewText: These worked really well, but our dog hated having them on. We still think they are a really good product!We got a large, and they fit our 74 pound German Shepherd quite well.The trick is to start slow. Show the dog the goggles and give him a treat for showing interest in them. Put them on and then reward, reward, reward! We gave him kibble for a full minute while he wore the glasses, then removed them. Do that each day for longer periods of time, and less treats, but always reward. Eventually, they won't need the constant praise, but getting a treat every time the glasses get put on helps associate these with good things.Once he got used to having them on and ignoring them, we made it so he only went outside during the day while having these on, so he grew to associate them with food and walks, the same way he grew to associate his leash with outside time.I like that these are padded all the way around, he seems more comfortable with them, but they can get got, so don't leave them on all the time.

title: Bayer Seresto Flea and Tick Collar
reviewText: My dog had a tick problem... I had been treating it with an essential oil mix I made, and then a powder, and Vets Best Tick spray... it worked, but it wasn't perfect. I told his veterinarian about my methods, and she informed me it was time to stop being "homeopathic" and take care of my dog.I listened... I had 2 options, a topical or a collar. I got the collar because they assured me it was the safest, because if he had a reaction, or developed one, I could just take the collar off. This is the exact collar they recommended, and I bought it... I stopped using the all natural stuff, and just trusted that the issue was resolved.WRONG! Instead of 4-5 ticks, we were pulling off 20! Every time we'd pet him, we'd find ticks! He had one just now by his eye, and my husband found one in his ear! We tried tightening the collar, and I never took it off him... it did not help at all. If anything, I would almost say this collar attracted the ticks.My dog is a German Shepherd / Husky mix, and he had this collar on him daily for over two weeks. It is possible that it needs longer, it's possible that it wouldn't work because of his thick fur. There are so many possibilities... all I know is the amount of ticks increased.I am so angry about this... what an utter waste of money. I was coerced into purchasing it by my veterinarian,  and made to feel guilty because I was trying natural methods, and was made to feel like I was hurting my dog... I felt horrible, because it was never my intention to hurt him. I got him vaccinated, I only purchased food that was well rated and 5 stars by dogfoodadvisor.com, I strayed away from bad treats and read up on everything I could... but this collar? It let my dog be eaten alive! We were doing tick hunts and removing them several times throughout the day! It was never this bad with the natural remedies...Still feeling the guilt, I have switched him to Frontline Plus, as it is what people in my area have been recommending.  We put it on him yesterday, and have found a lot of dead ticks, but we're also still finding ticks on him, which we are removing, so I'm happier with it, but I am still waiting to see the full effect.The natural spray I used was this:12 drops Lavender oil, 15 drops Citronella oil, 15 drops Lemongrass oil, into 14oz of witch hazel. I got this from the wholedog.orgWhat seems to work best, however, is a 3 part mixture 1 part yarrow powder1 part neem powder1 part diatomaceous earth – Food gradeDust the dog with it bi-weekly... safe to use with topicals.I do admit, I have never seen a single flea on him... perhaps the collar helped with that.

title: Animal Essentials Plant Enzymes & Probiotics, 300 gram
reviewText: My two dogs have tummy issues from time to time, and one of them has an especially sensitive stomach.  I did have them both on a human grade probiotic, but after Max's last horrific gastric upset, his vet and I discussed why human probiotics don't always address canine needs.  So I researched a little and found this product that is recommended in a Whole Dog Journal article (a publication I trust greatly), and decided to try it out.  It's been over a month now, and not only is this product more reasonable in cost than what I was spending on high quality human grade probiotic for both my dogs, it appears to be working MUCH better.  Max has never had poo this consistently "good" for so long.  If I find that down the line something changes, I will update.

title: Cat Mate Large Cat Door White
reviewText: It does the trick, but I find the little buttons that keep the flap shut a bit of pain.  I would rather have gone with a cat door with the slide on cover, in hindsight.  You have to be sure that the flap is in the correct position before you push the tabs/buttons together to keep it closed, or it will not be secure.  We learned this the hard way when we first got the door - our cat escaped.  Luckily for us, he was waiting outside the door in the a.m.  Now we have an enclosed catio on the other side of the cat door, so it's not as much of an issue, but still a bother.  Also, because the flap is hard plastic, it took our cat some time to get used to it, and feel comfortable going through it.  Lastly, be careful when purchasing the "recommended" insert that is listed with product on the Amazon page (the section where they say so-and-so purchased this and this together)...the one that was listed with this is the WRONG size and does not go with this cat door.

title: Nature's Miracle Just for Cats Urine Destroyer Formula, 32-Ounce Pour Bottle
reviewText: A must-have for any cat owner. Saturation followed by laundering seems to eliminate the odor (to my nose, at least, which is much less sensitive than a cat's nose). The product does have an odor of its own, but it isn't offensive, and it washes out in the laundry, though it's harder to get out of carpet. Based on examination of linens with a UV light, I suspect that once an item with urine has been laundered once, the Nature's Miracle is less effective at breaking down the residual urine.PS: I maintain that every pet owner should have a waterproof protector on his or her mattress. Nature's Miracle is better than nothing for a mattress with urine or vomit, but shielding the mattress is better still.

title: Ezydog Zero Shock 48" Leash
reviewText: Disclaimer: My dog weighs 90 pounds. She likes to chase small furry things like rabbits without warning while on walks.Now that that ^^ is out of the way, I can say I love this leash. Does it stop her from pulling? No, but it makes it more bearable when she does decide to pull like a tug boat and try to dislocate my shoulder because something cute and furry ran -over there- and she must chase it. This leash is a good length for walks, jogs, etc. The shock absorber helps when there's any pull back from myself or the dog.The traffic control loop does work, but it also goes flat if your dog is pulling, and you're trying to grab onto that. In all honesty, I should teach my dog to heel better, and I shouldn't need the traffic control loop whenever she sees something of interest. That being said, the loop does what it's for, if you can get ahold of it. I use that feature most when we're at a pet store and someone is letting their dog get too close, or I'm concerned that she might decide to shoplift :)All in all, this is a high quality, durable leash that has withstood over a year of beating from my giant lapdog who likes to chase things. Thumbs up.

title: Drinkwell Platinum Pet Fountain 168oz
reviewText: The unit appears to be made well, and trust me, I did everything to get my cat to drink out of this fountain, including only using bottled water, so the filter would remain clean.No matter what, she was not going to drink from this, so after a week, I just returned it.  I do not blame the unit or it's manufacturing.  However, looking at the way the filter and pump sit, I can tell this would require a lot of Maintenon like most of these cat fountains.My answer was simple...I bought a people fountain!  I went with an inexpensive one. Thinking my cat would reject this also.  I also went with a three tier system because I thought if she saw the water flowing it might help.  Well, guess what...she loves it!  As I said, it's a junky fountain made out of plastic, but from far away, it actually looks real and is illuminated and under $20!  The model I got was the Home medic illuminated 3 tier WFL-SLVS, Envirascape.I had the first model of that die after about 6 months because I was just using water from the refrigerator filter.  I cleaned it and it worked fine, but I felt it was too dirty for my cat, so I gave it to a friend as a fountain for their house.  I bought 3 more so I have spares in the garage.  I just love the lights.  I keep it on a bottom shelve where she likes to sit and play with the water.I am looking for a new people fountain for her now, but that one works.I hoped I helped you cat lovers out there at least a little.  Happy New Year!!

reviewText: I have now finally given up on trying to get my cat to be interested in catnip. :(I read all the great reviews about how much fun it is to see your cat go wild after whiffing a bit of this stuff. title: Ultimate Touch Gentle Slicker, Cats
reviewText: My cat liked to be brushed, but only with a plastic bristled brush (like one of mommies).  I originally got her a Furminator, which I think is the best brush on the market for removing fur.  I use to use it on my dog and remove a bag full of fur at a sitting...but I digress.When I first tried the gentle cat slicker, I was very carful brushing my cat.  She did not look happy at all.  Then, for the first time ever I found out my cat can scream (in a VERY threatening manner!).  I had never seen this before and I panicked thinking I had hurt her.  However, I looked and everything looked fine, so I tried to brush her again.  This time my cat growled at me, and I think would have scratched my eyes out if she could have.  Oh my, not a pleasant thought.It was at that time I decided this is not the brush for us, as I like my eyes.I rated the brush average, as my cat is finicky and being a rescue cat who knows what happened to her with a slicker brush as a kitten.  Still,  after hearing the sound my kitty put out ( right out of the Exorcist) I have no intentions of using this brush again and I will donate it to the animal rescue in my area,

reviewText: I wasn't expecting much when I was asked to review these squeakers.  I mean, what can you say about a squeaker anyway?  Well, you can say a lot.To start with, I tested every single squeaker and they all worked. I tested 20 of each size, for a total of 60, and not one dud. You now have a $10 toy and a happy fido.I would not hesitate to buy these again from this seller.  Highly recommend.

title: Pet Supply Imports Herm Sprenger Chrome Plated Training Collar with Quick Release Snap
reviewText: If you know anything about training you know that this brand is the best prong out there. Unfortunately I was given erroneous info on how to size this and when I ordered it for my 6 month old male pit puppy who is 60 # I was told to get a medium. The prongs on the medium however are very large and heavy duty and poked literal holes in his neck during training with his trainer that have yet to heal. So be sure to match the prongs to the dog. The small is just as effective without causing major neck damage.Followup 6/11/14 I love the prong, it is the only way I can control my big boy and he responds really well to it. I seldom have to do any corrections at this point unless he comes across another dog. I tried using a heavy duty Martingale instead but it is as if he knows that it isn't going to control him and he is just horrid with it on, as soon as I put on the prong again he is immediately mellow and obedient without corrections.  However.....The quick release is dangerous in my opinion, it has come open at least 7-8 times on my boy, luckily I grabbed him quick enough and we were at home. It is only attached to the link of the small chain by the claw and it is not reliable. My boy is now 10 months old and 72#, and can be dog aggressive, I cannot take a chance on this anymore. I am ordering a new regular one, the links aren't that hard to use to take it on and off and I have never used the quick release part anyway. If you need to be be 100% sure you will have control DO NOT BUY THE QUICK RELEASE

title: ABO Gear Aussie Dog Backpack
reviewText: Overall I like this pack a lot but for the moment it is a bit big for my 6 month old 60# pit puppy. The pockets are VERY large so when all I put in was a large water bottle on one side and some weight equalization stuff on the other side the stuff kind of hung down below his belly line and bugged him a lot. Plus the water sloshing confused him, he kept looking back at his side, like "what the heck is that?" I have now bought some special water bottles that are smaller and have sippers but that actually have a cup attached to the bottom for him to drink out of, greatest find ever, at the 99 cent store no less. I plan to put one of those on each side, one for me and one for him, and then add some other stuff to add more weight but he still is going to have to kind of grow into this pack. I didn't want to have to buy another one in like 6 months or so when he is bigger (gonna be over 100#!) so sized it for future. He can wear it now but all the straps are tightened all the way so have to tuck the straps in all over because there is a lot of straps hanging. It is going to take some getting used to for both of us. He went to "boot camp" and is extremely well trained for walking, he literally walks only a couple inches away from your left leg so I found that the backpack kept bumping into me and I kind of tripped a couple times. It definitely threw off our already established rhythm which was perfect so we will have to work on the backpack rhythm a bit!As far as the backpack itself, it is made of cotton, it is army green which I like, very soft and well made, I think it will much more comfortable to have him in cotton when summer comes than those nylon ones. It looks like it would easily wash, although I WILL put in in a lingerie bag so it doesn't get all tweaked and air dry it. He looks like GI JOE when he wears it which I though was pretty cute. All in all a great investment!

Who knows if I will ever get a result from this. If they tell me again bad sample you can bet I will take my money back!
